34
00:01:23.335 --> 00:01:25.275
to provide the best contribution we can.

35
00:01:26.095 --> 00:01:28.435
That's why we are here with two submissions,

36
00:01:28.495 --> 00:01:30.115
our main NZ airport submission

37
00:01:30.535 --> 00:01:33.435
and, uh, convening the joint infrastructure practitioners

38
00:01:33.435 --> 00:01:35.555
group letter that you may have also seen.

39
00:01:37.035 --> 00:01:39.875
Airports occupy a distinctive place in the planning system.

40
00:01:40.445 --> 00:01:41.715
Their fixed infrastructure

41
00:01:41.865 --> 00:01:43.995
with investment horizons measured in decades.

42
00:01:44.785 --> 00:01:46.715
They serve functions that extend well

43
00:01:46.715 --> 00:01:48.075
beyond their physical boundary,

44
00:01:48.875 --> 00:01:50.775
and they sit at the center of significant

45
00:01:50.835 --> 00:01:54.535
and growing communities of activity, businesses, employers,

46
00:01:54.955 --> 00:01:58.655
supply chains that have located, co-located precisely

47
00:01:58.655 --> 00:01:59.975
because the airport is there.

48
00:02:00.775 --> 00:02:03.865
That co-location creates a planning challenge as much

49
00:02:03.865 --> 00:02:05.145
as an economic opportunity,

50
00:02:05.775 --> 00:02:08.665
because the same growth that reflects an airport's success

51
00:02:09.215 --> 00:02:12.025
also generates pressure on its ability to operate.

52
00:02:13.405 --> 00:02:15.425
How the planning system manages that tension,

53
00:02:15.895 --> 00:02:17.985
whether it protects airport operations

54
00:02:18.045 --> 00:02:21.465
or progressively constrains them, even unintentionally,

55
00:02:22.345 --> 00:02:23.945
determines not just the airport's future,

56
00:02:24.485 --> 00:02:26.585
but the future of everything that that depends on it.

57
00:02:27.285 --> 00:02:29.925
And that's why the architecture of these bills means,

58
00:02:30.105 --> 00:02:31.165
uh, so much to us.

59
00:02:33.245 --> 00:02:35.785
The bills are by design enabling legislation.

60
00:02:35.975 --> 00:02:38.985
They create architecture, the substance,

61
00:02:39.325 --> 00:02:40.705
the detailed policy content

62
00:02:40.775 --> 00:02:44.405
that will determine day-to-day planning outcomes will follow

63
00:02:44.405 --> 00:02:45.565
through national instruments.

64
00:02:46.655 --> 00:02:49.285
These a structural consequence to this design.

65
00:02:50.535 --> 00:02:51.635
It means that the impact

66
00:02:51.635 --> 00:02:54.515
of the bills will only be fully understood once the shape

67
00:02:54.515 --> 00:02:56.915
and scope of national instruments are known.

68
00:02:57.825 --> 00:02:59.805
What that means practically is

69
00:02:59.805 --> 00:03:01.205
that you are approving a frame

70
00:03:01.265 --> 00:03:02.765
before the walls have been built.

71
00:03:04.145 --> 00:03:06.805
The most important question this committee can ask is

72
00:03:06.805 --> 00:03:07.965
what should be settled now

73
00:03:09.085 --> 00:03:11.545
and what should be delegated to others to determine later?

74
00:03:12.495 --> 00:03:14.385
Some delegation is absolutely appropriate,

75
00:03:14.845 --> 00:03:17.925
but some things are two foundational

76
00:03:18.025 --> 00:03:19.565
to leave to that future process.

77
00:03:20.945 --> 00:03:23.525
It also changes the weight you should give to what might

78
00:03:23.525 --> 00:03:26.805
otherwise come across as process style requests

79
00:03:27.875 --> 00:03:30.775
in a conventional system, a requirement, for instance,

80
00:03:30.775 --> 00:03:33.855
that infrastructure providers be consulted on national

81
00:03:33.855 --> 00:03:35.335
directions and spatial plans

82
00:03:36.225 --> 00:03:39.255
might be considered a procedural nicety, useful, obvious,

83
00:03:39.715 --> 00:03:42.295
but something that you as members might expect will be

84
00:03:42.295 --> 00:03:45.555
worked out in practice in a top-down

85
00:03:45.765 --> 00:03:47.355
nationally directive system.

86
00:03:47.705 --> 00:03:51.115
It's something else entirely national direction cascades

87
00:03:51.115 --> 00:03:52.955
through spatial plans, through local plans

88
00:03:52.975 --> 00:03:56.755
and consenting problems surface when a spatial plan is

89
00:03:56.755 --> 00:03:58.155
locked in incompatible land use

90
00:03:58.175 --> 00:04:00.355
or a consent condition reflects a standard

91
00:04:00.355 --> 00:04:02.515
that was never tested against operational reality.

92
00:04:03.625 --> 00:04:06.715
Codifying engagement requirements then is not about adding

93
00:04:06.715 --> 00:04:08.115
process for its own sake,

94
00:04:08.175 --> 00:04:11.115
but about guaranteeing the quality of the decisions

95
00:04:11.115 --> 00:04:13.115
that everything else in the system depends on.

96
00:04:13.975 --> 00:04:15.915
So it encourage you to look at those requests.

97
00:04:15.945 --> 00:04:19.635
With that in mind, one of the core objectives

98
00:04:19.635 --> 00:04:22.315
of the reforms is to reduce the cost complexity

99
00:04:22.335 --> 00:04:24.635
and adversarials of resource management.

100
00:04:24.945 --> 00:04:27.955
With that in mind, I also recommend the committee adopt a

101
00:04:27.955 --> 00:04:30.355
consistent analytical lens across all of the hearings.

102
00:04:31.205 --> 00:04:33.275
Other provisions of these bills clear enough

103
00:04:33.465 --> 00:04:35.355
that they can be applied predictably,

104
00:04:36.215 --> 00:04:38.595
or do they leave room for competing interpretations

105
00:04:38.595 --> 00:04:40.115
that will ultimately be tested

106
00:04:40.385 --> 00:04:43.475
through litigation rather than resolved through plans

107
00:04:44.345 --> 00:04:45.735
where the answer is the latter.

108
00:04:46.395 --> 00:04:47.895
We suggest the committee should act now.

109
00:04:48.045 --> 00:04:49.415
Otherwise, the objectives

110
00:04:49.415 --> 00:04:53.335
of the reforms may not be met in this regard.

111
00:04:53.375 --> 00:04:56.175
The areas of highest concern to us are the relationship

112
00:04:56.175 --> 00:04:59.455
between goals and how conflicts between them are resolved

113
00:04:59.955 --> 00:05:01.215
and the definition and treatment

114
00:05:01.215 --> 00:05:02.655
of infrastructure across the bills.

115
00:05:04.885 --> 00:05:07.905
Infrastructure protection is the ask every infrastructure

116
00:05:07.905 --> 00:05:10.745
submitter has in common and for good reason.

117
00:05:11.855 --> 00:05:13.675
The first reason is irreversibility.

118
00:05:14.705 --> 00:05:17.835
When a sensitive land use establishes near an airport, such

119
00:05:17.835 --> 00:05:20.235
as noise sensitive residential subdivision,

120
00:05:21.305 --> 00:05:23.155
that decision compounds over time.

121
00:05:24.055 --> 00:05:27.115
The houses are built, people move in expectations form,

122
00:05:27.495 --> 00:05:30.075
and those expectations become politically real.

123
00:05:31.435 --> 00:05:33.895
At that point, the airport's ability to operate

124
00:05:33.915 --> 00:05:37.175
as designed is constrained, not by a formal decision,

125
00:05:37.355 --> 00:05:39.295
but by accumulated fact on the ground.

126
00:05:40.375 --> 00:05:42.795
The planning system did not interrupt that sequence,

127
00:05:43.375 --> 00:05:45.195
so the airport must now manage what

128
00:05:45.195 --> 00:05:46.515
around, what grew up beside it.

129
00:05:47.725 --> 00:05:49.415
That dynamic is almost impossible

130
00:05:49.415 --> 00:05:51.015
to reverse once it's set in.

131
00:05:51.195 --> 00:05:52.495
And we see this all around the world.

132
00:05:53.865 --> 00:05:56.725
So protective language in the legislation is what interrupts

133
00:05:56.725 --> 00:05:58.365
that sequence before it starts.

134
00:05:59.115 --> 00:06:02.045
Without that language, the burden falls on the operator

135
00:06:02.425 --> 00:06:04.765
to assert their position Through every consent process

136
00:06:05.035 --> 00:06:08.565
dispute and opportunities to fix things will be much rarer

137
00:06:08.565 --> 00:06:10.525
and considerably harder in the new system.

138
00:06:10.905 --> 00:06:12.805
That's why you'll see that desire

139
00:06:12.805 --> 00:06:14.765
for protective language coming through

140
00:06:14.765 --> 00:06:17.325
for many submitters in my kind of space.

141
00:06:18.745 --> 00:06:21.605
The second reason is about what a plan led system is really

142
00:06:21.665 --> 00:06:24.725
for the whole theory of these reforms is

143
00:06:24.725 --> 00:06:27.525
that conflict should be resolved early at the spatial

144
00:06:27.685 --> 00:06:28.685
planning and policy stage.

145
00:06:29.025 --> 00:06:31.045
So they do not recur at the consent stage

146
00:06:32.595 --> 00:06:35.245
without protective language in the primary legislation,

147
00:06:35.575 --> 00:06:38.005
plans cannot reliably give effect to that intent.

148
00:06:38.665 --> 00:06:41.005
The conflict is not resolved, it's just deferred

149
00:06:41.425 --> 00:06:44.285
and it will reappear in problems downstream.

150
00:06:46.285 --> 00:06:47.575
This is why we're recommending

151
00:06:47.575 --> 00:06:50.215
that the legislation not just natural national direction,

152
00:06:50.485 --> 00:06:53.375
contain affirmative protections for the operational

153
00:06:53.675 --> 00:06:56.175
and functional requirements of existing infrastructure.

154
00:06:57.555 --> 00:06:59.925
This means the legislation should clearly establish

155
00:06:59.995 --> 00:07:02.765
that reverse sensitivity is to be managed in regional

156
00:07:02.765 --> 00:07:05.525
and local plans, that infrastructure's operational

157
00:07:05.525 --> 00:07:07.165
requirements are to be predicted

158
00:07:08.035 --> 00:07:12.215
and a conditions imposed on infrastructure consents must be

159
00:07:12.215 --> 00:07:14.575
necessary proportionate and practically workable.

160
00:07:14.985 --> 00:07:17.895
These are things infrastructure needs from day one

161
00:07:18.235 --> 00:07:21.855
and across all governments, not from the national direction

162
00:07:21.855 --> 00:07:24.415
that may be shaped differently by governments over time.

163
00:07:25.975 --> 00:07:28.065
Airport submissions, including those from Aland

164
00:07:28.065 --> 00:07:30.825
and Christchurch airports will provide rich information on

165
00:07:30.825 --> 00:07:32.905
the need to safeguard airport operations.

166
00:07:32.925 --> 00:07:36.305
And I commend them to you. These aren't theoretical issues.

167
00:07:37.065 --> 00:07:39.075
They're risks that quite frankly,

168
00:07:39.225 --> 00:07:41.075
keep airport managers awake at night

169
00:07:42.495 --> 00:07:43.915
to deliver well-planned growth.

170
00:07:43.995 --> 00:07:45.875
Airports must be able to service that growth

171
00:07:45.875 --> 00:07:47.155
and have a system that understands

172
00:07:47.155 --> 00:07:48.355
that right from the beginning.

173
